values:
When I was single, I briefly considered computer dating. ...As a punchline to a comic strip. I ended up just using a walrus, because walruses are always funny. 

I never thought it was a good idea to fill out some online application, telling total strangers about yourself as if you're filling out a job application (most jobs don't come with the prospect of sex, but that's neither here nor there). 

It's got to be a humiliating experience, because in order to divulge anything of interest about yourself, you've got to examine yourself. You've got to look at every unfortunate, nasty, crusty aspect of your life, and make sure you <i>do not</i> mention them. Even if your real hobby is clipping your toenails and marvelling at how many walls in your apartment they bounce off before disappearing (I hold the record in my household, with 3), you've got to say you spend your free time reading Camus. If you're a shallow person, and all you care about are humongous breasts, there's apparently an uncontrollable urge to preface that by saying "I want someone who's beautiful on the inside, not just on the outside." If you lie, your relationship is doomed, because you can't start a relationship based on a lie. If you tell the truth, odds are you'll end up with somebody who assumed you were lying, and read "between the lines" that you like being lied to in return.

All that aside, there&#8217;s an even more fundamental flaw: computers don&#8217;t know people. They know 1&#8217;s and 0&#8217;s, but they don&#8217;t know chemistry (unless it&#8217;s a computer in a chem lab). I could be wrong, but that&#8217;s what I believe. 

And my belief was proven right yet again, when I tried clicking on the LiveJournal link that's supposed to find the individual most compatible with me. Mind you, I graduated from Berkeley, think the Second Amendment applies only to militias, not individuals, don&#8217;t believe in the war in Iraq, and am still waiting for that last chad to be found in Florida. LiveJournal found, as my ideal pen-pal, Bob, a card-carrying member of the NRA and Bush supporter, whose hobbies are &#8220;hunting, hunting, and hunting.&#8221;

Bob was not amused. Even though I began my e-mail with &#8220;Walrus.&#8221;
